\abstract{Persuasive messages lead a largely unexplored "social life" in which they compete and interact with other related and possibly contradictory messages (their "peers") in the information environment. Communication science has extensively studied and optimized individual message types (e.g., pro- or anti-alcohol messages), but has rarely directly compared competing messages to each other. This omission creates a knowledge gap concerning the differences and similarities in the effects of competing messages, as well as the mechanisms underlying these effects. Across three studies, we directly compared a diverse set of alcohol-related messages with their real-world competitors (pro-, anti-, and non-alcoholic messages from professional and peer sources) to understand the relative impact of these messages on alcohol craving and the mechanisms driving these effects. We found that the effects of pro-alcohol (vs. non-alcoholic) messages were significantly larger than the effects of anti-alcohol messages, especially among frequent binge drinkers. Emotional responses and perceived familiarity with the alcohol content emerged as relevant mechanisms for the effects of both pro- and anti-alcohol messages. However, both mechanisms were more strongly linked to alcohol craving in response to pro- compared to anti-alcohol messages. This raises concerns about the effectiveness of anti-alcohol messages that target these processes when viewed in direct competition with pro-alcohol information, for instance, on social media. Our work highlights that studying the real-world competition and interactions between different types of persuasive messages is crucial to understanding and predicting message effectiveness.}

\keywords{alcohol craving, anti-alcohol messages, persuasion, alcohol marketing, emotions, familiarity}

