Persuasive messages live largely unexplored "social lives". Within rich information environments, each message interacts and competes with its "peers", that is other messages which are relevant to the same attitude or behavior and which may (not) be congruent with the focal message (\cite{hendriks_social_2018, stautz_immediate_2016, young_effectiveness_2018, scholz_neural_2019}). These interactions likely create interference between message effects and, thereby, complicate the prediction of message effectiveness. For instance, like most daily choices, alcohol consumption has pros and cons. It is a social catalyst, associated with good friends and fun times (\cite{duckworth_transitions_2021}), but also a leading cause of death and disease across many countries (\cite{oecd_avoidable_2016}). In line with this ambiguity, diverse stakeholders, from alcohol brands, to public health officials, to party-loving friends and concerned family, seek to influence alcohol consumption. Their voices create rich information environment and frequent exposures to alcohol-related messages varying in valence (pro/anti-alcohol) and source (peers or professionals). Extensive prior work has examined individual message types (e.g. exclusively pro- messages; \cite{jernigan_alcohol_2017} or anti-alcohol messages; \cite{young_effectiveness_2018}), but how do alcohol-related messages differing in valence and source compare in their effects on alcohol craving? Do they exert influence through similar or different psychological mechanisms? Across three exploratory studies, we present evidence highlighting the importance of examining the social life of persuasive messages through direct comparisons of message types.

\subsection{Persuasion in Complex Information Environments}

How do people make decisions in complex, ambiguous information environments such as that surrounding alcohol? Neuroscientists and decision scientists have demonstrated that the human brain is capable of seamlessly weighting myriad factors relevant to a given decision very quickly (\cite{busemeyer_cognitive_2019}). This is reflected in behavior change and decision-making theories like the Reasoned Action Approach (\cite{fishbein_predicting_2010}) and Identity-Value Model (\cite{berkman_finding_2017}), which describe an integration process where diverse information relevant to a given choice (e.g. social norms and attitudes) is integrated and weighed to inform a decision (\cite{levy_comparing_2011, falk_persuasion_2018}). In other words, when deciding whether to consume alcohol, individuals likely consider multiple alcohol information types, such as both pro- and anti-alcohol information from peers and professionals. 

One small aspect of this integration process has been studied fruitfully in communication research on the interactions between mass media messages and message-related interpersonal communication. The Two-Step Flow model (\cite{katz_two-step_1957, katz_personal_1955}) posits that mass media influences its target group indirectly through the gate-keeping efforts of \textit{opinion leaders} who further distribute and interpret mass media messages within their social network. Empirical evidence shows that message-related interpersonal communication impacts both who is exposed to mass media content and how message receivers are affected (\cite{southwell_roles_2007, jeong_effect_2017}). This can result in either enhanced (\cite{van_den_putte_interpersonal_2011}) or diminished (\cite{david_social_2006}) message effects. Research on alcohol consumption similarly shows that the effects of anti-alcohol messaging are partially mediated by the valence (pro- or anti-alcohol) of subsequent interpersonal conversations (e.g. \cite{hendriks_talking_2012}), and the extent to which daily drinking decisions are (unhealthily) impacted by pro-alcohol interpersonal conversations depends partially on an individual's sensitivity to anti-alcohol persuasive messaging (\cite{scholz_neural_2019}).

This work highlights the importance and potential contributions of research into the social life of persuasive messaging, but only considers one specific type of message interactions. The broader persuasion literature remains split into disconnected fields, each focusing on individual message types. For instance, research on social influences on alcohol consumption (e.g. \cite{borsari_peer_2001}) rarely intersects with work on professionally produced messaging (e.g. \cite{jeong_effect_2017,jernigan_alcohol_2017}), and work on pro-alcohol messages rarely also considers anti-alcohol message effects. The result is incomparable data employing diverse operationalizations and theoretical foundations, and a sizeable knowledge gap regarding the nature of the real-world competition between message types: 

Research Question (RQ)1: What are the relative effects of alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source on alcohol craving?  

\subsection{Competition Across Valence and Source Dimensions}

To answer RQ1, we exposed research participants to alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source to compare these message types in their effects on alcohol craving. Alcohol craving is a key predictor of consumption [CITE RAMIREZ 2014], has been shown to be sensitive to message exposure manipulations [Noel Lakhan 2021, Stautz Marteau 2016], and can ethically and validly be measured on repeated trials, allowing a within-subject design in which each person is immersed in a rich information environment. 
 
First, we sought to establish the effectiveness of our sample of pro- and anti-alcohol messages in enhancing or diminishing alcohol craving, respectively, by comparing them to closely matched non-alcoholic messages. 

H1: Alcohol craving will be higher in response to pro- versus non-alcoholic messages and non-alcoholic versus anti-alcohol messages. 

While H1 constitutes a conceptual replication of prior work [CITE], the existing literature lacks information regarding the specificity of these effects. Message effects are more consequential for public health interests to the extent that they specifically modulate craving for alcohol as opposed to beverages more generally.

H2: The effect of exposure to pro- versus anti-alcohol messaging on craving is stronger when craving is assessed for alcoholic rather than non-alcoholic beverages. 

Once these basic relationships are established, our design can support important novel questions about the relative effect sizes of messages varying in valence. To reduce (risky) alcohol consumption, is it more effective to produce more anti-alcohol messaging or further regulate pro-alcohol messaging? To our knowledge, only two existing studies addressed this question, but have produced contradictory results with limited generalizability. Stautz and Marteau (CITE 2016) randomly assigned participants to view either 10 anti-alcohol, pro-alcohol, or non-alcoholic advertisements. Relative to non-alcoholic stimuli, anti-alcohol messages significantly reduced drinking urges, while pro-alcohol stimuli did not have significant effects. Using the same design, Stautz and colleagues (CITE 2017) found consistently larger (but not significantly different) effects of the pro- compared to anti-alcohol videos, each relative to non-alcoholic ads. It remains unclear how these results translate to new stimuli, especially non-video ads, or to complex information environments which contain more than one message type per person. The present study compares relative effect sizes of a larger sample of static pro- and anti-alcohol messages (relative to non-alcoholic stimuli) and does so in a within-subject design.

Although both professional and peer-produced alcohol information has been documented carefully and shown to be impactful [CITES}, we are not aware of direct comparisons of their effects on alcohol consumption. Are carefully designed campaigns more successful in influencing alcohol craving than relatable peer-produced messages or vice versa? Do source effects differ across pro- and anti-alcohol messages? Here, we extent the limited prior work comparing pro- and anti-alcohol content by including both professionally and peer-produced stimuli.

\subsection{Drivers of Alcohol Craving}

In order to design reliable, and generalizable message effects, it is crucial to understand the underlying psychological mechanisms (e.g. \cite{scholz_invoking_2023}). Moreover, in the context of complex information environments, quantifying the relative importance of a mechanism may help to predict the likelihood and nature of interference between two message types. For instance, if both pro- and anti-alcohol messaging are attempting to affect alcohol consumption by portraying self-relevant circumstances, which of these appeals may exert greater influence? 

RQ2: Is alcohol craving in response to alcohol-related messages varying in valence and source driven by similar or different psychological mechanisms?

It is impossible to consider the full breadth of potential mechanisms of persuasion in a single study. Here, we examined RQ2 on the example of two particularly central mechanisms in the context of the alcohol information environment: emotions and familiarity.

\subsubsection{Emotions}
Affective responses are frequent targets of persuasive messages across diverse behavioral domains (\cite{dillard_affect_2012,poels_role_2019,hornik_quantitative_2016,nabi_emotion_2017}) and, importantly, they are often the focus of both pro- and anti-alcohol messaging. One of the few direct comparisons between pro- and anti-alcohol messaging suggests that pro-alcohol messages are more likely to evoke positive affective responses whereas anti-alcohol messages are more focused on negative affective responses (\cite{stautz_impact_2017}).

Negative affect is targeted by professional anti-alcohol messaging by emphasizing diverse negative outcomes of (excessive) alcohol consumption such as catastrophic accidents (fear) caused by drunk drivers (shame/guilt) or inappropriate social situations (shame; \cite{becheur_emotions_2007,duhachek_guilt_2012}). A small minority of studies has further examined the potential utility of positive emotions such as humor (\cite{lee_college_2018,previte_shaping_2015}). Professional pro-alcohol messaging often targets positive emotions by highlighting positive aspects of alcohol consumption. For instance, partying and relaxation are among the major themes in US TV advertising (\cite{morgenstern_content_2015}). Common messages depict individuals consuming alcohol in enjoyable, often social situations where individuals are shown laughing, relaxing, and generally expressing positive affect. Positive and negative affective responses to pro- and anti-alcohol (\cite{chen_alcohol_2005}) messaging, respectively, are related to message effectiveness. 

The literature on the effects of emotions in peer-produced alcohol content is limited, but early content analyses are suggestive. Peer-produced messages generally do not have a clear persuasive intent (\cite{hendriks_alcohol-related_2017}) and, as a result, are likely less strategic and less consistent in their use of emotional appeals. While peer-produced pro-alcohol messages generally seem to mimic professional pro-alcohol content in that they often express positive emotions related to drinking alcohol, peer-produced anti-alcohol messages may be more emotionally ambiguous. For instance, a social media post may depict a negative outcome of drinking not unlike those displayed in professional anti-alcohol campaigns (e.g. a bike accident), but display it in a humorous light as the unfortunate, yet funny outcome of an epic night. Generally, the strong pro-alcohol norm among young adults disincentivizes purely negative peer-produced anti-alcohol content (\cite{beullens_display_2013}). Given the state of the literature, it is difficult to predict the relationship between emotional responses to peer-produced alcohol content and alcohol craving.

In sum, psychological experiences to different types of alcohol messaging are quite varied. To meaningfully compare mechanisms underlying the effects of different message types to each other, we need to measure responses that are relevant across message types and could, thus, theoretically lead to inferences between message effects. Following the example of prior work (STAUTZ 2017), we thus assessed general positive and negative affective responses as opposed to specific emotions. Yet, treating these general measures as mediators of message effects on craving would require the questionable assumption that, for instance, positive affective responses to diffent alcohol message types are qualitatively similar. Instead, we compare how and how strongly related mechanisms (e.g. positive affect) are related to craving in response to different message types.

H3a: The strength of positive emotional responses to alcohol-related information will be positively associated with alcohol craving. 

H3b: The strength of negative emotional responses to alcohol-related information will be negatively associated with alcohol craving. 

H4: The effect hypothesized in H3a will be stronger (H4a) and the effect specified in H3b will be weaker (H4b) for professional and peer-produced pro-alcohol compared to professional anti-alcohol information. 

Besides the potentially special role of anti-alcohol peer-produced content, the existing literature does not support clear hypotheses about potential source effects. How do professional and peer sources compare in their elicitation of emotional responses and how are these responses linked to craving? We will explore these relationships here. 

\subsubsection{Familiarity}
We define familiarity as perceptions that a message shows characters who are 'like me' and/or a familiar situation. The literature discusses these types of familiarity under audience-character similarity (\cite{kim_effect_2016,bochner_effectiveness_1994}) and message self-relevance. Generally, familiarity is viewed as favorable to message effectiveness becaise ot enhances receivers' attention and the perceived relevance of the messages. In fact, creating familiar scenarios and characters are popular tailoring strategies that are linked to message effectiveness across domains (\cite{lustria_meta-analysis_2013,noar_does_2007}). Similarly, self-relevance is positively associated with persuasive effects (for a review see \cite{falk_persuasion_2018}). 

H5: The relationship between familiarity and alcohol craving will be moderated by valence so that the slope will be positive (leading to more craving) for pro-alcohol messages and negative (leading to less craving) for anti-alcohol messages. 

The relative effect sizes of these relationships are unknown but will be investigated here.

Content analyses of alcohol-related posts on social media suggest that pro-alcohol content is much more prevalent than anti-alcohol (REFS). More generally, strong pro-alcohol social norms among young adults likely create similar patterns of overexposure to pro- rather than anti-alcohol content through other mediated and interpersonal communication. Moreover, general self-serving biases (\cite{mezulis_is_2004}) and third-person effects [CITE] likely bias recipients of anti-alcohol information to underestimate their own similarities and familiarity with characters who are experiencing negative outcomes from drinking alcohol. Consequently:

H6: Pro-alcohol information will be perceived as more familiar than anti-alcohol information. 

Familiarity has been extensively studied in the context of professional messaging, but to a much lesser extent for peer-produced messages. Is familiarity a stronger driver of craving in response to peer or professional messages and do these effects differ for pro- and anti-alcohol content?

\section{Method}
We conducted three online studies to directly compare the impact of different types of alcohol-related messages on alcohol craving and to explore mechanisms of these effects. Study 1a established craving responses to a large sample of professional and peer-produced pro- and anti-alcohol messages. Study 1b further included professional- and peer-produced messages about non-alcoholic beverages as a comparison condition. Study 2 conceptually replicated Studies 1a/b using a subset of the same stimuli, new participants and a slightly different task design. All participants provided informed consent and applied procedures approved by the ethical review board at [UNIVERSITY ANONYMIZED FOR REVIEW] (#2020-PC-12672). All measures are available on our OSF page [LINK].

