\subsection{Data Analysis}

Although the existing literature supports a set of directional hypotheses the analyses presented here were not pre-registered and are, thus, exploratory.

First, we confirmed that the stimuli were perceived as intended using the two manipulation checks measured in Study 1a/b (see Supplementary Materials for details). 

In addition, we z-scored craving ratings for all analyses including data from both Study 1a/b and 2, because of the difference in the rating scales (see Table \ref{tab:measures}). We further created a familiarity index by computing the average of the self-relevance and familiarity ratings per trial (Cronbach's alpha for item scores averaged on the stimulus-level = 0.97, 95%CI[0.96,0.98]).

We then conducted two types of analyses. First, we estimated condition effects on beverage craving using multi-level mixed regression models as implemented in R's lmerTest package (\cite{kuznetsova_lmertest_2019}) to account for the nested structure of the data. Second, we conducted stimulus-level analyses, aggregating over participants.

Given the differences in the rating scales (see Table \ref{tab:measures}), beverage craving was z-scored within study for analyses including data from both Studies 1a/b and 2.

\section{Results}

\subsection{Information valence (H1), but not source, influences alcohol craving}

First, we examined within-person effects of message valence and source on (standardized) alcohol craving in Studies 1a and 2, controlling for age, gender, binge-drinking and drinking frequency (Study 1a), AUDIT scores (Study 2), and accounting for random intercepts across participants and messages.  
Table \ref{tab:cravingTableMain} shows strong valence effects so that pro-alcohol messages lead to stronger alcohol craving than anti-alcohol messages. This valence effect is larger in Study 1a, in which craving was measured directly following stimulus exposure, whereas Study 2 measured craving in response to alcohol cues shown after each stimulus exposure (see Figure \ref{fig:FigureAlcValTask}). There was no main effect of source. We further did find strong evidence of interactions between valence and source (see Supplementary Materials for details).  

