\subsubsection{Drinking habits are associated with message receptivity}

A possible explanation for the ineffectiveness of anti-alcohol messaging (compared to non-alcoholic content) is that anti-alcohol messages are generally targeted at high risk (binge) drinkers and thus do not (and are not intended to) resonate with low risk drinkers. Yet, in an exploratory follow-up analysis of Study 1b, we found that those who reported higher binge drinking frequency, on average, reported higher alcohol craving and a higher sensitivity to pro-alcohol (compared to non-alcoholic) stimuli, but not to anti-alcohol stimuli (Table \ref{tab:bingeTable}; Figure \ref{fig:bingeFigure}).

